  "time_ut": 1656134927,
  "original_lang": "si",
  "original_title": "\u0dc0\u0dd2\u0daf\u0dda\u0dc1 \u0db8\u0dd4\u0daf\u0dbd\u0dca \u0dc3\u0db1\u0dca\u0dad\u0d9a\u0dba\u0dda \u0dad\u0db6\u0dcf \u0d9c\u0dd0\u0db1\u0dd3\u0db8 \u0d9c\u0dd0\u0db1 \u0db1\u0dc0\u0dad\u0db8 \u0dc3\u0dd3\u0db8\u0dcf\u0dc0\u0db1\u0dca",
  "text_idx": {
    "en": {
      "title": "Latest restrictions on holding foreign currency",
      "author": "unknown",
      "body_lines": [
        "The Central Bank of Sri Lanka announces the latest revision regarding the limits, terms and conditions of holding foreign currency.",
        "With the aim of attracting foreign currency held by the public to the formal banking system, the Minister of Finance has issued the following regulations under Section 8 of the Foreign Exchange Act No. 12 of 2017.",
        "1.) The amount of foreign currency that a resident in Sri Lanka can hold in his possession is USD. 15,000 to USD 10,000 or any equivalent amount of foreign exchange.",
        "2.) Provision of a general amnesty period of 14 working days from the effective date (June 16, 2022) for persons residing or resident in Sri Lanka for the following:",
        "i) to deposit into a personal foreign currency account or a business foreign currency account, as specified in the rule;",
        "ii) To sell to an authorized dealer (Licensed Commercial Bank or National Savings Bank)",
        "It is further informed that the Central Bank of Sri Lanka reserves the right to initiate action in accordance with the provisions of the Foreign Exchange Act against persons who violate this provision and keep foreign currency in their possession at the end of the amnesty period.",
        "a) to associate with any licensed commercial bank or National Savings Bank;",
        "b) To refer to the above amendments made by Gazette Notification No. 2284/34 dated 16th June 2022 (Extra Special) under Section 8 of the Foreign Exchange Act through the official website of the Department of Foreign Exchange www.dfe.lk,",
        "c) The Central Bank of Sri Lanka further states that it is possible to contact the Department of Foreign Exchange through the e-mail address dfe@cbsl.lk or telephone numbers 011-2477255 or 011-2398511."
      ],
